Introduction

This notebook outlines a solution to the exercise using the tidymodels package to implement the modeling. I have decided to implement two models, MARS and SVM with polynomial kernel.

Exercise Instructions

Instructions adapted from Kuhn and Johnson (2013)1.

Exercise 6.3 describes data for a chemical manufacturing process. Use the same data imputation, data splitting, and pre-processing steps as before and train several nonlinear regression models.

  1. Which nonlinear regression model gives the optimal resampling and test set performance?
  2. Which predictors are most important in the optimal nonlinear regression model? Do either the biological or process variables dominate the list? How do the top ten important predictors compare to the top ten predictors from the optimal linear model?
  3. Explore the relationships between the top predictors and the response for the predictors that are unique to the optimal nonlinear regression model. Do these plots reveal intuition about the biological or process predictors and their relationship with yield?

Data splitting and resampling using rsample

In previous analyses with this data set, the observation with row no. 108 has caused issues. There are a number of zeros for this row in columns where all other rows have values greater than zero (sometimes in the thousands). This may be missing data encoded as zero, but for now I will remove this observation as it acts as an extreme outlier and has a detrimental effect on the performance.

Split the data into a training and test set, and then proceed with preprocessing and modeling.

# Rename the response to `y`:
df1 <- df1 %>% 
  rename(y = Yield)

# Remove the outlier point mentioned above:
df1 <- df1[-108, ]

# Split data:
set.seed(1)
splits <- initial_split(df1, prop = 0.7)
df_train <- training(splits)
df_test <- testing((splits))

Create folds for 10-fold cross-validation:

folds <- vfold_cv(df_train, v = 10)

Solution

MARS

Training Data

Build a MARS model and train using cross-validation.

We will preprocess the data to center and scale the predictors, impute missing values, remove near-zero variance predictors and remove highly correlated predictors (this is the same recipe as used in exercise 6.3).

# Recipe:
rec1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_knnimpute(all_predictors(), neighbors = 5) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors(), threshold = 0.9)

# Model:
mars_mod <-
  mars(num_terms = tune(), prod_degree = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("earth") %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow1 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = mars_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Tuning grid:
mars_grid <- expand_grid(num_terms = 2:10, prod_degree = 1:2)

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter7/data/mars_cv_7.5_2.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  mars_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  mars_cv <- 
    workflow1 %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = mars_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(mars_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

mars_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rsq") %>% 
  mutate(prod_degree = factor(prod_degree)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(num_terms, mean, color = prod_degree)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "num_terms", y = "R Squared (CV)",
       title = "MARS tuning parameter error profile.") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2, 10, 2)) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Select the best model and store the training \(R^2\):

mars_best <- mars_cv %>% 
  select_best("rsq")

# Store the training R^2:
rsq_train <- mars_cv %>% 
  show_best("rsq") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Finalize the workflow by updating it to use the best model:
final_wf <- 
  workflow1 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(mars_best)

# This extracts the parameters in the final model (this code is clunky, could probably be made simpler):
wf <- final_wf %>% workflows::pull_workflow_spec()
num_terms <- wf$args$num_terms[2] %>% as.character()
prod_degree <- wf$args$prod_degree[2] %>% as.character()

# Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:
mars_fit_final <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits) 
! train/test split: preprocessor 1/1: NA/Inf replaced by maximum positive value
# Store test error:
rsq_test <- mars_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rsq") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")

Store the \(R^2\) values and parameters:

RSQ <- tibble(
  framework = "tidymodels",
  engine = "earth",
  model = "MARS",
  rsq_train = rsq_train,
  rsq_test = rsq_test,
  parameters = str_interp("num_terms: ${num_terms}; prod_degree: ${prod_degree}")
)

Use the predictions to make diagnostic plots

Collect the predictions from the final fit and make diagnostic plots:

preds <- mars_fit_final %>% 
  collect_predictions() %>% 
  mutate(residual = y - .pred)

p1 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, y),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_abline(color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Predicted", y = "Observed")

p2 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, residual),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
             color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Predicted", y = "Residual")

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(title = "Diagnostic Plots (MARS)")

SVM with polynomial kernel

Training Data

Build an SVM with a polynomial kernel and train using cross-validation.

I will use the same preprocessing as the MARS model.

# Model:
svm_poly_mod <-
  svm_poly(cost = tune(), degree = tune(), scale_factor = tune()) %>% # leave `margin` (0.1) as the default
  set_engine("kernlab") %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

# Workflow:
workflow2 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = svm_poly_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1) 

# Tuning grid:
svm_poly_grid <- expand_grid(cost = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1),
                             degree = 1:2, 
                             scale_factor = c(0.25, 0.5, 1))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter7/data/svm_poly_cv_7.5_2.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  svm_poly_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  svm_poly_cv <-
    workflow2 %>%
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = svm_poly_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(svm_poly_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

svm_poly_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rsq") %>% 
  mutate(cost = factor(cost),
         degree = factor(degree)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(scale_factor, mean, group = cost, color = cost)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "scale_factor", y = "R Squared (CV)",
       title = "R Squared resampling profiles for linear and quadratic support vector machines.") +
  facet_wrap(~degree, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Select the best model and store the training \(R^2\):

svm_poly_best <- svm_poly_cv %>% 
  select_best("rsq")

# Store the training R^2:
rsq_train <- svm_poly_cv %>% 
  show_best("rsq") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Finalize the workflow by updating it to use the best model:
final_wf <- 
  workflow2 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(svm_poly_best)

# This extracts the parameters in the final model (this code is clunky, could probably be made simpler):
wf <- final_wf %>% workflows::pull_workflow_spec()
cost <- wf$args$cost[2] %>% as.character()
degree <- wf$args$degree[2] %>% as.character()
scale_factor <- wf$args$scale_factor[2] %>% as.character()

# Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:
svm_poly_fit_final <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits) 
! train/test split: preprocessor 1/1: NA/Inf replaced by maximum positive value
# Store test error:
rsq_test <- svm_poly_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rsq") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")

Store the \(R^2\) values and parameters:

RSQ <- rbind(RSQ,
                 c(framework = "tidymodels",
                   engine = "kernlab",
                   model = "SVM (Polynomial)",
                   rsq_train = rsq_train,
                   rsq_test = rsq_test,
                   parameters = str_interp("cost: ${cost}; degree: ${degree}; scale_factor: ${scale_factor}")))

Use the predictions to make diagnostic plots

Collect the predictions from the final fit and make diagnostic plots:

             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +

  labs(x = "Predicted", y = "Observed")

p4 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, residual),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +

             color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +

Metrics

Compare the performance of the non-linear models in this exercise to the linear model (PLS) from exercise 6.3:

RSQ_linear <- readRDS("/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter7/data/APM_7_exercise_6_3_RSQ.RDS")
rbind(RSQ, RSQ_linear) %>% 
  mutate(rsq_train = round(as.numeric(rsq_train), 3),
         rsq_test = round(as.numeric(rsq_test), 3)) %>% 
  arrange(-rsq_test)

The MARS model and PLS model had comparable test \(R^2\) values. The better PLS model (PLS 2) had the outlier point removed which improved the \(R^2\) value.

My MARS model used the ManufacturingProcess32, ManufacturingProcess09 and ManufacturingProcess13 variables. My PLS model used ManufacturingProcess32, ManufacturingProcess09 and BiologicalMaterial06.

Plot the relationship between important predictors and response

Use the same code as in exercise 6.3 to plot the relationship of these predictors with the response.

Use prep() and bake() to apply the preprocessing recipe to ALL of the data before making the plots:

df_pp <- rec1 %>% # rec1 for the MARS model
  prep() %>% 
  bake(df1) %>% 
  cbind(df1$y)
NA/Inf replaced by maximum positive valueNA/Inf replaced by maximum positive valueNA/Inf replaced by maximum positive value

Plot the top 3 predictors identified above:

p1 <- ggplot(df_pp, aes(ManufacturingProcess09, y)) +
  geom_point(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_smooth(se = F, color = "indianred1")

p2 <- ggplot(df_pp, aes(BiologicalMaterial06, y)) +
  geom_point(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_smooth(se = F, color = "indianred1")

p3 <- ggplot(df_pp, aes(ManufacturingProcess13, y)) +
  geom_point(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_smooth(se = F, color = "indianred1")

p4 <- ggplot(df_pp, aes(ManufacturingProcess32, y)) +
  geom_point(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_smooth(se = F, color = "indianred1")

(p1 + p2) / (p3 + p4)

ManufacturingProcess09, BiologicalMaterial06 and ManufacturingProcess32 have a positive relationship with the response. ManufacturingProcess13 has a negative relationship. If these manufacturing processes can be controlled, then altering these steps in the process to have higher (or lower) values could improve the overall Yield of the process. A statistically designed experiment could be used to investigate a causal relationship between the settings of these processes and the overall yield.

ManufacturingProcess09 seems to have the most linear relationship, while the others are clearly non-linear.
